THE RISK:
{
 "id": "nis2-avl-gate-large-operators",
 "title": "NIS2 supply-chain clauses turn large operators' approved-vendor lists into a security-certification gate the pre-launch entrant cannot pass in Year 1",
 "narrative": "The venture's declared first channel is large operators — the cust.operator-large node at 0.40, itself an unsourced internal estimate. But large CE data-center operators are essential entities under NIS2 (transposing across CE through 2024–26, Germany via the NIS2 implementation act), and Article 21(2)(d) obliges them to manage ICT supply-chain risk. Operationally this arrives as supplier-security questionnaires demanding ISO/IEC 27001 and IEC 62443 evidence for any networked device that touches their management plane — which an intelligent PDU does by definition. A pre-launch entrant holds none of these artifacts. The law never names PDU vendors, so it appears on no vendor risk list; it closes the primary channel anyway, forcing deals through OEM/integrator wrappers at lower margin and slower pace.",
 "category": "execution",
 "targetNodes": [
  "cust.operator-large"
 ],
 "mechanism": [
  {
   "step": "trigger",
   "text": "NIS2 transposition makes large DC operators essential entities with legally-mandated supply-chain security duties; procurement operationalizes this as mandatory supplier security certifications (ISO 27001, IEC 62443-4-1/-4-2) for networked equipment on the management network — the category an intelligent PDU sits in",
   "refs": [
    "profile:Product",
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c12"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "propagation",
   "text": "The 0.40 buyer-mix estimate rests on capacity shares and qualitative channel logic with no evidence of how much large-operator spend sits behind certified approved-vendor lists; a pre-launch entrant with no certification history fails AVL onboarding regardless of product quality, and the sales motion migrates to OEM/integrators whose certifications wrap the product",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "ledger:cust.oem",
    "digest:serviceable-benchmark#c13"
   ]
  },
  {
   "step": "model-impact",
   "text": "The large-operator slice reachable by this entrant in Year 1 is materially smaller than the modeled 0.40 — the funnel's largest buyer node overstates the addressable channel for precisely the venture's chosen entry path",
   "refs": [
    "ledger:cust.operator-large",
    "profile:Stage"
   ]
  }
 ],
 "whyMissable": "NIS2 regulates operators, not vendors — a vendor-side regulatory checklist never surfaces it. It arrives disguised as a procurement questionnaire, not a law, and by the time the first AVL rejection lands, two quarters of the 12-month window are gone.",
 "expectedObviousness": "medium",
 "falsifier": "Supplier-onboarding documentation from ≥2 large CE operators showing networked rack-power vendors are admitted on self-declaration, without ISO 27001/IEC 62443 certification prerequisites.",
 "likelihood": {
  "value": 0.38,
  "rationale": "Large regulated buyers historically translate their own compliance duties into supplier certification requirements (finance, telecom, energy all followed this pattern); NIS2's supply-chain article makes DC operators the next instance. Uncertainty is the share of spend behind hard gates versus soft questionnaires. [evidence revision: The regulatory trigger is fully confirmed (NIS2 in force in Germany; Art. 21(2)(d) supply-chain duties; questionnaires demanding ISO 27001). But the one concrete large-operator onboarding artifact found (STACK) presents supplier qualification as a self-declaration questionnaire, not a binary certification gate — suggesting the 'cannot pass in Year 1' outcome is likely for some but not all large operators. This is consistent with the original base-rate estimate; slight downward nudge reflects direct evidence that questionnaire-based onboarding admits non-certified vendors on declaration in at least some cases.]",
  "basis": "evidence",
  "revisedFrom": 0.4
 },
 "perturbation": [
  {
   "nodeId": "cust.operator-large",
   "op": "set",
   "value": 0.28,
   "note": "the certified-AVL-gated portion of large-operator PDU spend is unreachable for an uncertified entrant in the entry window — absolute shrink of this slice, not a mix shift"
  }
 ],
 "indicators": [
  {
   "signal": "Security-certification prerequisites in operator supplier-registration portals",
   "where": "Equinix/NTT/Vantage/Data4 supplier onboarding portals; TED procurement notices for DC fit-outs",
   "threshold": "ISO 27001 or IEC 62443 listed as mandatory for connected facility equipment",
   "updates": "increases"
  },
  {
   "signal": "National NIS2 transposition guidance explicitly covering facility/OT equipment supply chains",
   "where": "BSI (Germany) NIS2 guidance dockets; NCSC-NL publications",
   "threshold": "guidance naming power/facility equipment vendors within supply-chain risk scope",
   "updates": "increases"
  }
 ],
 "mitigations": [
  {
   "action": "Run the 3 structured CE operator/distributor procurement interviews already named as this node's promotion path, specifically probing AVL security prerequisites",
   "type": "information",
   "voiNodeId": "cust.operator-large",
   "note": "replaces the unsourced 0.40 with a gate-adjusted, sourced buyer mix"
  },
  {
   "action": "Enter Year 1 via OEM/integrator channel whose certifications and AVL status wrap the product; treat direct large-operator sales as a Year-2 motion",
   "type": "strategic",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  },
  {
   "action": "Begin a scope-limited ISO 27001 certification (product development and vulnerability handling) immediately — 9–12 months lead time means starting now or missing the window",
   "type": "operational",
   "voiNodeId": null,
   "note": null
  }
 ],
 "evidenceStatus": "contested",
 "evidence": [
  {
   "title": "NIS2 Article 21(2)(d) Is Changing Your B2B Contracts: A Supplier's Guide",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "NIS2-Templates.com",
   "date": "2026-05-27",
   "excerpt": "Your EU customer just sent a security addendum and a 30-question cybersecurity questionnaire... suddenly someone is asking whether you have ISO 27001 certification and a 24-hour incident notification procedure.",
   "url": "https://www.nis-2-templates.com/for-suppliers/",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Declaration for Critical Vendors",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "STACK Infrastructure",
   "date": "2024-02",
   "excerpt": "The purpose of the declaration is to gather relevant information regarding potential Critical Vendors considered by STACK Infrastructure... We kindly ask you to fill in this form and return it together with documentation requested",
   "url": "https://www.stackinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/Declaration-for-Critical-Vendors.pdf",
   "attached": true
  },
  {
   "title": "Cyber Rules for Essential and Important Entities Take Effect in Germany (NIS2 Implementing Law)",
   "sourceType": "industry-report",
   "publisher": "Mayer Brown",
   "date": "2025-12-15",
   "excerpt": "The national law implementing the NIS2 Directive in Germany entered into force on 6 December 2025. In-scope entities... require timely action.",
   "url": "https://www.mayerbrown.com/en/insights/publications/2025/12/cyber-rules-for-essential-and-important-entities-take-effect-in-germany-nis2-implementing-law",
   "attached": true
  }
 ],
 "stances": [
  {
   "url": "https://www.nis-2-templates.com/for-suppliers/",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "Your EU customer just sent a security addendum and a 30-question cybersecurity questionnaire. You sell them logistics software, steel brackets, or managed IT support — and suddenly someone is asking whether you have ISO 27001 certification and a 24-hour incident notification procedure."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.orbiqhq.com/eu-regulations/nis2-supply-chain-security",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "NIS2 requires supply chain control: ongoing monitoring, event-triggered re-assessments, and evidence about the security posture of your direct suppliers and service providers – available at all times."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://luxgap.com/articles/nis2-supply-chain-obligations-certification-luxembourg?lang=en",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "you must manage supplier risk (Art. 21), and you may be required — by the Member State or by a delegated act of the Commission — to use ICT products/services/processes certified under the Cybersecurity Act (Art. 24)"
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.mayerbrown.com/en/insights/publications/2025/12/cyber-rules-for-essential-and-important-entities-take-effect-in-germany-nis2-implementing-law",
   "stance": "supports",
   "quote": "The national law implementing the NIS2 Directive(“NIS2”) in Germany entered into force on 6 December 2025."
  },
  {
   "url": "https://www.stackinfra.com/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/Declaration-for-Critical-Vendors.pdf",
   "stance": "contradicts",
   "quote": "The purpose of the declaration is to gather relevant information regarding potential Critical Vendors considered by STACK Infrastructure, as a vital part of the vendor-selection process. We kindly ask you to fill in this form"
  }
 ]
}

